    <span class="post-date">Jul 12th 2026</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>
      <span class="post-opener"
        >Today I officially benched 225 pounds.</span
      >
    </p>

    <div class="lift-card" aria-label="225 pound bench press milestone">
      <div class="lift-card-label">ACHIEVEMENT UNLOCKED</div>
      <div class="lift-total"><strong>225</strong><span>LB</span></div>
      <div
        class="lift-barbell"
        role="img"
        aria-label="A 45 pound bar loaded with two 45 pound plates on each side"
      >
        <span class="lift-sleeve lift-sleeve-left"></span>
        <span class="lift-plate lift-plate-left-outer"></span>
        <span class="lift-plate lift-plate-left-inner"></span>
        <span class="lift-bar"></span>
        <span class="lift-plate lift-plate-right-inner"></span>
        <span class="lift-plate lift-plate-right-outer"></span>
        <span class="lift-sleeve lift-sleeve-right"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="lift-equation">
        <span>45 lb bar</span>
        <b>+</b>
        <span>4 &times; 45 lb plates</span>
        <b>=</b>
        <strong>225 lb</strong>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      Two 45-pound plates on the left. Two on the right. No tiny plates hiding
      the math. Just the bar, four big circles, and a number I have spent a long
      time walking toward.
    </p>
    <p>
      225 is not a world record. It does not need to be. It is a receipt for all
      the ordinary days that looked too small to matter: showing up, adding a
      rep, fixing the form, sleeping, eating, failing, and coming back.
    </p>
    <hr class="post-divider" />
    <p>
      For years, two plates looked like a wall. Today it became a door.
      I pressed through it.
    </p>
    <p>
      I will celebrate this one. Then I will do the less glamorous work of
      turning a personal record into a weight I own.
    </p>
    <p class="lift-closing"><strong>Old ceiling: 225. New floor: loading...</strong></p>
